Title: Reckoning — Kestrel's Choice
Source: V3
Act: III

===

~ Fleur holds. Kestrel sees what she has done. Not redemption — reckoning. The truth is told. Fleur stands at the beginning of her real training.

The city is burning. The demon is loose. Fleur stands in the wreckage of everything she believed.

But Fleur does not collapse. In the worst moment of her life, Silas's teaching reasserts itself — not the knowledge Silas withheld, but the lesson she gave every day without words. You show up. You serve. You do the work even when it costs you everything. Even when no one is watching. Even when it won't be enough.

Fleur gives everything she has to shield the townsfolk. Not with demon power — that road is ash. With her body, her hands, her voice. She pulls people from burning buildings. She throws herself between the fire and the fleeing crowd. She is not controlling the demon. She is not wielding power. She is doing what Silas did in the village — serving people who are afraid, without recognition, without reward, at the cost of herself. Her face and arm are seared. She does not stop.

Kestrel sees Fleur in the fire and the calculation breaks.

This is not the demon's puppet. This is not the weapon Kestrel engineered. This is Silas's student — half-trained, burning, giving everything for people who don't even know her name. And Kestrel recognises what she has done. Not in the abstract — in the specific. She engineered this. She told the Alderman about the demon. She steered Fleur toward the fire. She used a grieving child the same way the Alderman used his prophecy: she told Fleur that power was a gift, that she was special, that she was chosen. She did exactly what Silas was afraid of. She did exactly what broke herself during the war.

Kestrel is inches from her revenge. The Alderman's ceremony is in ruins. His prophecy is burning. She could walk away and let the fire finish what she started a decade ago.

She doesn't. She makes her choice. Not redemption — reckoning.

Kestrel reaches into the fire. She takes the demon's bargain onto herself, using the full discipline of her training — the real training, the years of dangerous, unglamorous work that the Order understood and the prophecy denied. The demon art is not a spell. It is a physical battle of wills. Kestrel has been burned so many times she no longer fears the pain. She contains the demon. It costs her.

And then she tells Fleur the truth. There is no Chosen One. There never was. The Alderman made it up. The demon used it. Kestrel used it. Silas tried to protect Fleur from it but only left her more vulnerable. The only power that is real is the kind you earn — slowly, painfully, with no guarantee of success. What Fleur did in the fire — throwing herself between the flames and the people with nothing but her own body — that was real. Not because it was special. Because it was work.

The demon is sealed back in the lantern. Kestrel is diminished — perhaps dying, perhaps simply spent. The Alderman's ceremony is ruins, his prophecy a joke, but his political machinery grinds on. The world has not been saved by a single act of fire.

What has changed is Fleur.

The final image: Fleur holds the iron lantern. Her face is scarred. Her illusions are gone. And for the first time, she is ready to begin.
